# Identity, billing, and webhook contracts

## Rule

Auth, billing, subscriptions, entitlements, and webhooks are contract-heavy. A
small metadata mismatch can create lost access, double billing, unpaid access,
or unrecoverable reconciliation gaps.

## Metadata and identity parity

1. The key written at checkout or external-resource creation must match the key
   read by webhooks and reconciliation jobs.
2. User ID, org/team ID, email, customer ID, subscription ID, price ID, product ID,
   and internal plan IDs must have one canonical mapping layer.
3. Admin/owner/support overrides must be symmetric across UI, API, jobs, and
   scripts.
4. Existing external resources must be updated when mutable fields drift; do not
   only set fields on create.

## Webhook discipline

1. Verify signatures before parsing trusted fields.
2. Use idempotency keys or processed-event records.
3. Handle duplicate, delayed, missing, out-of-order, and retry events.
4. Store enough raw event metadata for audit and replay, without secrets.
5. Treat clocks and timestamps carefully; validate units and time zones.
6. Keep webhook handlers deploy-skew tolerant when schemas or event names change.

## Entitlement discipline

1. UI gates and backend gates must match.
2. Loading states must not flash restricted/free state for paid users.
3. Denied API responses should explain the missing entitlement without leaking
   private billing details.
4. Scheduled jobs and background workers must enforce the same entitlement rules
   as interactive routes.

## Pre-commit check

- [ ] Metadata key written equals metadata key read.
- [ ] Webhook is signature-verified and idempotent.
- [ ] UI/API/job entitlement gates match.
- [ ] Existing external resources update mutable drift.
- [ ] Tests cover duplicate and out-of-order events.
